Standard C++ review — discuss main function and namespace collection; attributes of main & use of namespace

main function (role and attributes):

•	Entry point of every C++ program. Signature variants commonly used:

•	int main() — no arguments.

•	int main(int argc, char* argv[]) (or char** argv) — command-line arguments: argc count, argv array of C-strings.

•	Must return an int. Returning 0 typically indicates success; non-zero indicates error. If control reaches end of main without return, C++ implicitly returns 0.

•	main should be defined once in the program. It can call other functions, set up program state, and return status to the OS.


namespace (purpose and std):

•	Namespaces group names (types, functions, variables) to avoid name collisions.

•	Standard library content lives in the std namespace. Example: std::vector, std::cout.

•	You can introduce your own namespaces:

namespace mylib {
    void foo() { /*...*/ }
}

Use via mylib::foo();.

•	Two ways to access std:

1.	Fully qualify: std::cout << "Hello\n"; (recommended for clarity).

2.	using declarations:

-using std::cout; (imports one name).

 -using namespace std; (imports entire namespace — convenient but can cause name collisions, avoid in headers).



•	Namespaces can be nested and extended across translation units.


•	Short example showing main and namespace usage:

#include <iostream>
int main(int argc, char* argv[]) {
    std::cout << "Program name: " << (argc ? argv[0] : "unknown") << "\n";
    return 0;
}
